Private label jewelry — jewelry produced by a manufacturer and sold under your brand name — is one of the most accessible paths to building a jewelry business with genuine product differentiation. The model allows you to develop a distinctive design identity without owning production equipment or employing craftsmen, while accessing the production quality of established manufacturing facilities.

This guide outlines the practical steps for moving from concept to market with an OEM jewelry manufacturing partner.

**Step 1: Define Your Brand Position and Product Category**

Before approaching any manufacturer, you need clarity on two things: where your brand sits in the market (price tier, aesthetic identity, target customer), and what type of jewelry you intend to produce (rings, necklaces, earrings, bracelets — or a combination).

Your market position determines your material requirements. A brand selling at $80–$150 retail typically works in sterling silver 925 with rhodium or gold plating. A brand at $200+ retail may require gold vermeil (thick gold plating over silver) or solid gold alloy pieces. Your manufacturer needs to work in the appropriate materials for your price tier.

**Step 2: Develop Your Design Direction**

You do not need professional CAD files to approach an OEM manufacturer. Most manufacturers work from sketches, reference photographs, or a written brief. What you need is a clear sense of the aesthetic — the visual language, proportions, and design details that define your collection.

Gather reference images, sketch basic concepts, and identify the specific details that matter to you: stone shapes and sizes, setting styles, surface finishes, weight range. The more specific you can be, the more efficiently the manufacturer's design team can translate your brief into a production-ready CAD model.

**Step 3: Select a Manufacturer**

Evaluate prospective manufacturers on the criteria outlined below. Contact at least three manufacturers with the same brief to compare quotes, lead times, and communication quality before making a selection.

Key criteria: in-house production capability, minimum order quantity, sample process, material documentation, and responsiveness to your inquiry. A manufacturer who takes five days to respond to an initial inquiry will be a slow communicator throughout production.

**Step 4: Request Quotes and Review the Sample Process**

Send your design brief, material specifications, and target quantities to your shortlisted manufacturers. A professional OEM manufacturer will respond with a unit price breakdown, lead time estimate, and information about their sample process.

Sample fees are standard in OEM manufacturing — they cover the CAD design and prototype production time. Most manufacturers deduct sample fees from your first production order if you proceed. Review sample pricing and process carefully: a structured sample approval process (CAD → wax prototype → silver sample) protects you against costly production errors.

**Step 5: Approve Your Sample**

This is the most important stage in the production process. Review your approved sample against every specification: dimensions, weight, stone placement, surface finish, plating color and coverage, finding gauge (for earrings), clasp mechanism (for necklaces and bracelets).

Do not proceed to full production if any element of the sample is unsatisfactory. Manufacturers will reproduce samples until your specifications are met — within reason. Document your approval in writing.

**Step 6: Place Your Production Order**

Confirm the production order in writing with a purchase order specifying: design reference, quantity per SKU, material specifications, plating specifications, stone specifications, packaging requirements, and required ship date.

Retain the approved sample as your quality reference. If production output deviates from the approved sample in ways you consider significant, you have documentation to support a quality dispute.

**Step 7: Monitor Production Progress**

Request production milestone updates — photographs post-casting, post-polishing, and pre-shipment. Professional OEM manufacturers provide these as standard. These photographs allow you to identify any production issues before final inspection and give you visibility into your production timeline.

**Step 8: Final Inspection and Shipment**

Review the pre-shipment photographs carefully. For your first production run with a new manufacturer, consider requesting an independent quality inspection through a third-party service before shipment — particularly for larger orders.

Ensure you have all required documentation before goods ship: commercial invoice, packing list, and any material documentation required for import compliance in your destination market.

